…says 125 protesters arrested Worried about ongoing protests across parts of the country against xenophobic attacks on Nigerians in South Africa and the likely implication on security, the Inspector General of Police (IGP), Mr. Mohammed Adamu has ordered maximum security cover around embassies and foreign missions.
Also to be given adequate security attention, are foreign business interests across the country.
Zonal Assistant Inspectors General (AIGs), and Commissioners of Police across the 36 State commands and the Federal Capital Territory (FCT), have been directed to ensure immediate enforcement.
This was as the IGP further disclosed that a total of 125 protesters have since been arrested in connection with the ongoing demonstrations.
The Force Public Relations Officer (FPRO), DCP Frank Mba, who made the disclosure in a statement Wednesday, said the IGP’s order followed the attack on Shoprite ourlet in Lekki area of Lagos on Tuesday.
The directive came in the face of a similar protest Wednesday in Lugbe, a suburb of Abuja, by angry youths, who attempted an attack on Shoprite, one of the business concerns of South Africa in the country.
Also on Wednesday, an MTN outlet located at Mararaba, Karu Local Government Area of Nasarawa State, was torched by protesting youths, who were stopped from further violent action by anti-riot policemen.